<subSubSection box="[151,918,1375,1402]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,918,1375,1402]" box="[151,918,1375,1402]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,918,1375,1402]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,918,1375,1402]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
<taxonomicName authority="Prout, 1912" authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[151,481,1375,1402]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,329,1375,1402]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Hierochthonia</emphasis>
Prout, 1912
</taxonomicName>
and “ 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[557,580,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">H</emphasis>
.” 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[609,765,1375,1402]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">alexandraria</emphasis>
Prout, 1912
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="140" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1447,1978]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
Prout diagnosed the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[478,640,1447,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[478,640,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Hierochthonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[661,718,1447,1473]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Warren, 1901" authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1901" box="[834,1250,1447,1474]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Microloxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulverata">
<emphasis box="[834,1078,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Microloxia pulverata</emphasis>
Warren, 1901
</taxonomicName>
) using external characters as antennae bipectinate up to the last apical segments; hindwing with the subcostal vein fused with the fore margin of the discal cell near to its end; hindtibia provided with one pair of spurs (Prout 1912: 204). 
<bibRefCitation author="Hausmann, A." pageId="3" pageNumber="140" pagination="3 - 90" refId="ref4374" refString="Hausmann, A. (1996) The morphology of the geometrid moths of the Levant and neighbouring countries. Part I: Orthostixinae, Geometrinae. Nota lepidopterologica, 19 (1 / 2), 3 - 90." type="journal article" year="1996">Hausmann (1996)</bibRefCitation>
redescribed the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[484,646,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[484,646,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Hierochthonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
using 
<taxonomicName authority="Warren" authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1901" box="[722,953,1555,1582]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Microloxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulverata">
<emphasis box="[722,864,1555,1581]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">H. pulverata</emphasis>
Warren
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Pungeler. Comparison" authorityName="Pungeler. Comparison" baseAuthorityName="Pungeler" baseAuthorityYear="1902" box="[1008,1406,1555,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semitaria">
<emphasis box="[1008,1149,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">H. semitaria</emphasis>
Püngeler. Comparison
</taxonomicName>
of the characteristics of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[393,575,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alexandraria">
<emphasis box="[393,575,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">H. alexandraria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(also 
<figureCitation box="[645,759,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1398,1422]" captionTargetBox="[202,1386,800,1372]" captionTargetId="figure-205@1.[202,1386,800,1372]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Adult moths of the studied taxa. 1–2: Hissarica postalbida: 1—male, Tajikistan, Kondara 2—female, Kondara; 3–4: Xenochlorodes albicostaria: 3—male, Iran, Comèe, 4–female, Comèe; 5–6: Xenochlorodes olympiaria: 5—male, Dalmatia, Gravosa, 6–female, Griechenland, Delphi; 7–8: Hierochthonia pulverata, 7—male, Syria, 8—female, Syria; 9–11: Ratsa alexandraria: 9—Holotype, female, “Alexandergebirge”, 10—male, Kazakhstan, Kentau, 11—female, Kentau; 12–13: Ratsa? petitaria: 12—Lectotype, female, “Askhabad” 13—female, Turkmenistan, Imam-Baba." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5566152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5566152/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Figs 9–11</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[772,801,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1897,1921]" captionTargetBox="[253,1325,784,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-271@5.[248,1339,777,1872]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 22–26. Genitalia structures of Hierochthonia, Ratsa, gen. nov. and Xenochlorodes. 22: Hierochthonia pulverata: 22a—male armature, 22b—aedeagus, 22c—VIII sternite, 22d—lateral view; 23–24: Ratsa alexandraria: 23a—male armature, 23b—aedeagus, 23c—VIII sternite, 23d—lateral view, 24a—female genitalia, lateral view, 24b—female genitalia, ventral view; 25—female genitalia of Ratsa? petitaria; 26—female genitalia of Xenochlorodes albicostaria. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5566160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5566160/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">23</figureCitation>
) with those of southern species (
<figureCitation box="[1175,1277,1591,1618]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–13" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1398,1422]" captionTargetBox="[202,1386,800,1372]" captionTargetId="figure-205@1.[202,1386,800,1372]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–13. Adult moths of the studied taxa. 1–2: Hissarica postalbida: 1—male, Tajikistan, Kondara 2—female, Kondara; 3–4: Xenochlorodes albicostaria: 3—male, Iran, Comèe, 4–female, Comèe; 5–6: Xenochlorodes olympiaria: 5—male, Dalmatia, Gravosa, 6–female, Griechenland, Delphi; 7–8: Hierochthonia pulverata, 7—male, Syria, 8—female, Syria; 9–11: Ratsa alexandraria: 9—Holotype, female, “Alexandergebirge”, 10—male, Kazakhstan, Kentau, 11—female, Kentau; 12–13: Ratsa? petitaria: 12—Lectotype, female, “Askhabad” 13—female, Turkmenistan, Imam-Baba." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5566152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5566152/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Figs 7, 8</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1291,1320,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1897,1921]" captionTargetBox="[253,1325,784,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-271@5.[248,1339,777,1872]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 22–26. Genitalia structures of Hierochthonia, Ratsa, gen. nov. and Xenochlorodes. 22: Hierochthonia pulverata: 22a—male armature, 22b—aedeagus, 22c—VIII sternite, 22d—lateral view; 23–24: Ratsa alexandraria: 23a—male armature, 23b—aedeagus, 23c—VIII sternite, 23d—lateral view, 24a—female genitalia, lateral view, 24b—female genitalia, ventral view; 25—female genitalia of Ratsa? petitaria; 26—female genitalia of Xenochlorodes albicostaria. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5566160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5566160/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">22</figureCitation>
) indicates the following differences.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1447,1978]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
Both 
<emphasis box="[264,600,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
Hierochthonia-- 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1901" box="[455,600,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Microloxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulverata">H. pulverata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[661,681,1664,1689]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[699,823,1664,1689]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">semitaria--</emphasis>
possess long, flat postvaginal lamellae and roundish lateral sclerites attached to the ostium in female genitalia (
<bibRefCitation author="Hausmann, A." box="[823,1012,1699,1725]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" pagination="3 - 90" refId="ref4374" refString="Hausmann, A. (1996) The morphology of the geometrid moths of the Levant and neighbouring countries. Part I: Orthostixinae, Geometrinae. Nota lepidopterologica, 19 (1 / 2), 3 - 90." type="journal article" year="1996">Hausmann 1996</bibRefCitation>
, Figs 144, 145). These structures are missing in “ 
<emphasis box="[287,482,1735,1762]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
H.” 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[336,482,1735,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alexandraria">alexandraria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[537,698,1736,1762]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
“H.” 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Christoph" authorityYear="1887" box="[602,698,1736,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Eucrostes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petitaria">petitaria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
females (
<figureCitation box="[808,938,1735,1762]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1897,1921]" captionTargetBox="[253,1325,784,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-271@5.[248,1339,777,1872]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 22–26. Genitalia structures of Hierochthonia, Ratsa, gen. nov. and Xenochlorodes. 22: Hierochthonia pulverata: 22a—male armature, 22b—aedeagus, 22c—VIII sternite, 22d—lateral view; 23–24: Ratsa alexandraria: 23a—male armature, 23b—aedeagus, 23c—VIII sternite, 23d—lateral view, 24a—female genitalia, lateral view, 24b—female genitalia, ventral view; 25—female genitalia of Ratsa? petitaria; 26—female genitalia of Xenochlorodes albicostaria. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5566160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5566160/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Figs 24, 25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1447,1978]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
The valva in male genitalia of typical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[615,777,1771,1797]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[615,777,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Hierochthonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a medial harpe (
<figureCitation box="[1002,1088,1771,1797]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1897,1921]" captionTargetBox="[253,1325,784,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-271@5.[248,1339,777,1872]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 22–26. Genitalia structures of Hierochthonia, Ratsa, gen. nov. and Xenochlorodes. 22: Hierochthonia pulverata: 22a—male armature, 22b—aedeagus, 22c—VIII sternite, 22d—lateral view; 23–24: Ratsa alexandraria: 23a—male armature, 23b—aedeagus, 23c—VIII sternite, 23d—lateral view, 24a—female genitalia, lateral view, 24b—female genitalia, ventral view; 25—female genitalia of Ratsa? petitaria; 26—female genitalia of Xenochlorodes albicostaria. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5566160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5566160/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Figs 22</figureCitation>
), and aedeagus is spoon shaped (distally dilated) with a complex apical sclerotization. However, “ 
<emphasis box="[909,1107,1807,1834]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
H.” 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[961,1107,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alexandraria">alexandraria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
has a tubular aedeagus with two thorn shaped cornuti on the vesica, and a simple valva (
<figureCitation box="[822,907,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURES 22–26" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1897,1921]" captionTargetBox="[253,1325,784,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-271@5.[248,1339,777,1872]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 22–26. Genitalia structures of Hierochthonia, Ratsa, gen. nov. and Xenochlorodes. 22: Hierochthonia pulverata: 22a—male armature, 22b—aedeagus, 22c—VIII sternite, 22d—lateral view; 23–24: Ratsa alexandraria: 23a—male armature, 23b—aedeagus, 23c—VIII sternite, 23d—lateral view, 24a—female genitalia, lateral view, 24b—female genitalia, ventral view; 25—female genitalia of Ratsa? petitaria; 26—female genitalia of Xenochlorodes albicostaria. Scale bar, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5566160" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5566160/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). Prout (1912) stressed the peculiar venation of hindwing with Sc free when characterizing “ 
<emphasis box="[663,996,1879,1905]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[663,831,1879,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hierochthonia</taxonomicName>
” 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[850,996,1879,1905]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alexandraria">alexandraria</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. We use this synergy of differences in wing venation and in male and female genitalia characteristics to separate “ 
<emphasis box="[1002,1022,1916,1941]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">H</emphasis>
.” 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1912" box="[1049,1195,1915,1941]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hierochthonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alexandraria">
<emphasis box="[1049,1195,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">alexandraria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a new genus of its own, 
<taxonomicName authority="Viidalepp &amp; Kostjuk" authorityName="Viidalepp &amp; Kostjuk" authorityYear="2021" box="[213,520,1951,1977]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Ratsa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[213,277,1952,1977]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">Ratsa</emphasis>
Viidalepp &amp; Kostjuk
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[531,637,1951,1978]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[531,631,1951,1977]" pageId="3" pageNumber="140">gen. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
will be described below for this species.
</paragraph>
